(114, 1, 'Section 7 - Security', '', 49, '<section class=\"g-bg-purple g-color-white g-py-100\">\r\n<div class=\"container\">\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-6 align-self-center text-center g-overflow-hidden g-mb-50 g-mb-0--md\"><img class=\"img-fluid w-75\" src=\"../../assets/img/inline/inline11.png\" alt=\"Image Description\" data-animation=\"fadeInUp\" data-animation-delay=\"0\" data-animation-duration=\"1000\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-6 align-self-center\">\r\n<div class=\"u-heading-v2-3--bottom g-brd-white g-mb-30\">\r\n<h2 class=\"h1 u-heading-v2__title text-uppercase g-font-weight-700\">Security</h2>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"g-font-size-18 g-line-height-2 g-mb-30\">\r\n<h5>Access Control List</h5>\r\n<p>The access of urls of your application is protected by an access control list (ACL) module. It gives an access of an url dependending on the user profile.<br /> The cms provide the following user profiles :<br /> - \'anonymous\' : it allows an access to your public web pages<br /> - \'guest\' : it allows an extranet access<br /> - \'user\' : this profile can create, modify your web site but it can not publish or administrate back-office users<br /> - \'admin\' : it is an extension of the \'user\' profile. It allows to publish and administrate the back_office users</p>\r\n<h5>Back-office and Extranet Login</h5>\r\n<p>For the back-office login or the extranet login, the login forms provide by default a captcha field and a csrf token.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</section>', NULL, NULL, 'content', '', '', '2019-01-18 18:44:39', '', '', '', 0, 0, NULL),
